{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_018CZkMmgbqYuM9EXGiNSpiW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YEAH8jVpVwgxySNmf17h7M","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves the meaning of the source text, not just a word-for-word substitution.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Verifying semantic coherence and meaning preservation requires calling the real neural translation API and evaluating its output. Mocking the translator hides failures where the real model produces degraded or incoherent output. To catch this failure, you need a semantic evaluator (another AI model, or human review) that assesses whether the translation preserves meaning. A pure Unit test with a mock translator would always pass because the mock can be configured to return any string.","test_description":"Call the real translation API with diverse test inputs across different languages and domains (e.g., idioms, technical text, slang). Use an automated semantic evaluator (e.g., a second LLM comparing source-target semantic similarity, or BLEU/METEOR metric against reference translations) to verify outputs preserve meaning and exhibit grammatical coherence. Catch real failures like model degradation, deployment issues, or API misconfiguration that break translation quality.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the translation API returns a 503 error, the service transparently falls back to the dictionary-based translator without returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Error handling logic can be tested with mocking (mock the API to return 503), but the fallback lookup depends on a real SQLite database. A Unit test with fully mocked d